, 
<collectingCountry id="2CD24C9BFFB3FFE96E98FCEFFBACA885" box="[1000,1081,882,903]" name="Guyana" pageId="23" pageNumber="1536">Guyana</collectingCountry>
, French Guiana, and 
<collectingCountry id="2CD24C9BFFB3FFE96C0FFC12FE55A8A7" box="[383,448,911,933]" name="Brazil" pageId="23" pageNumber="1536">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFB3FFE96DC2FC29FE1FAF06" pageId="23" pageNumber="1536" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFB3FFE96DC2FC29FE1FAF06" blockId="23.[178,1085,948,1029]" pageId="23" pageNumber="1536">
Etymology: The generic epithet is a compound name stemming from the Latin 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFB3FFE96DC2FC4FFF7BA8E5" box="[178,238,978,999]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="1536">forma</emphasis>
(= form) and the Greek 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFB3FFE96C9EFC4FFD80A8E5" box="[494,533,978,999]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="1536">isos</emphasis>
(= equal). I refer to the similar body form among the species of this genus.
</paragraph>
